If he have no interest in the fertile vales of Hellas, we cannot ask him to lay out capital in any speculative ven— ture. At the same time, we think that the seven or eight years’ occupation of the land ought to have yielded him sufficient income to enable him to ac- quire a permanent interest in some one or other of its allotments.

But we are not attempting to vindicate the gene- ral prosecution of classicai studies, What we desire is simply to reiterate the question—whether you, who now possess the key to the storehouse of old-world wisdom, to ‘⁴ a rich garden of study,'' will suffer it to rust, or whether you will let it still hang on the ring along with those appliances of „ learning which you must always carry about with you—whether, possessing now the medium of ac- cess, we might call it the masonic sign of appeal to those old worthies of the Greek calendar of wis- dom and of heroism, you will tacitly drop their ac- quaintance, even if you should not have the heart deliberately to “ break with’' them. This is the question: it is one, not of setting about or of leav- ing alone, but of holding or of letting drop—not a question of making a new reservoir, but of look- ing to the repair of one already with much toil dug
